  <static seed="1305" source="Contrib/PCC/Math95/ComplexFractions/ComplexFractions6.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{5+\frac{1}{t-9}}}{{\frac{1}{t-9}-\frac{1}{6}}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{6\mathopen{}\left(5t-44\right)}{-t+15}, t\ne 9</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{5+\frac{1}{t-9}}}{{\frac{1}{t-9}-\frac{1}{6}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{5+\frac{1}{t-9}}</m> and <m>{\frac{1}{t-9}-\frac{1}{6}}</m>, which is <m>{6\mathopen{}\left(t-9\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{5+\frac{1}{t-9}}}{{\frac{1}{t-9}-\frac{1}{6}}} \amp = \frac{({5+\frac{1}{t-9}})\cdot{6\mathopen{}\left(t-9\right)}}{({\frac{1}{t-9}-\frac{1}{6}})\cdot{6\mathopen{}\left(t-9\right)}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{5\cdot 6\mathopen{}\left(t-9\right)+\frac{1}{t-9}\cdot 6\mathopen{}\left(t-9\right)}}{{\frac{1}{t-9}\cdot 6\mathopen{}\left(t-9\right)-\frac{1}{6}\cdot 6\mathopen{}\left(t-9\right)}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{30\mathopen{}\left(t-9\right)+6}}{{6-\left(t-9\right)}} , t\ne9 \\
    \amp = \frac{{30t-270+6}}{{6-t+9}}, t\ne9  \\
    \amp = \frac{{30t-264}}{{15-t}}, t\ne9 \\
    \amp = {\frac{6\mathopen{}\left(5t-44\right)}{-t+15}, t\ne 9}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factors <m>t-9</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>t \ne 9</m>.</p>
</solution>
